The head of the White House will arrive tomorrow with his wife Michelle in the north-western metropolis and will be busy all the time.
First, he visits the Nobel Institute, where he meets for the first time with the five committee members who elected him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The couple then planned a meeting with Norwegian King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit reaches its climax with the ceremony where Obama takes over the prestigious award.
He received the award as the fourth U.S. president, but only as the third to receive the award directly in office.
The White House has already warned that Obama will talk about the war in Afghanistan when the price is taken over.
The president does not want to shy away from this issue because he knows that he is taking over the prize as a president who is currently waging war in two countries.
He reinforced the war efforts a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forget to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the gold medal, the diploma and the check over ten million Swedish kroner (about 24 million Czech kroner).
He intends to donate the money for charitable purposes, but has not yet decided on a concrete charitable work.
The event programme will then include a banquet with the President and his wife, in which the Prime Minister and another 250 guests will be present in addition to Norway’s King and Queen.
From the very beginning, Obama was very reluctant about the price.
He suggested, for example, that he felt that he did not fully deserve the prize.
He also repeated several times that the price is not just for him, but for everyone who aspires to the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he stated that this is a "call to action" for him.
