They have proven that the substances referred to as metallocarborates have an effect on the protein that is responsible for increasing the HIV virus.
The metal carbonates are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the virus proliferation in a different way than all the drugs used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists arrive at new ‘improved’ compounds, which have been prepared on the basis of knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the viral protein.
The metal carboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multiplicity cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Home-made and persistent virus
HIV protease is the protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus cleavage caused by the HIV protease, no mature infectious virus particles would emerge.
When we turn off the HIV protease, we also turn off the virus’s proliferation in the patient’s body, the scientists explain in a press report published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the paper, which was published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which are then systematically changed further.
Something weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against HIV proteases is tested in the reagent glass, also against their persistent (resistant) variants, which were obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metallocarborane on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as in the clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect on the resistant variants against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action as well as its further properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical formations, makes the metal carbonates interesting compounds for further research on the development of effective anti-HIV drugs, says Pavlina Rezacova, Head of the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Head of the Institute of Organic Chemistry, Pavlina Bizacova.
