The cradle of dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other flesh-eating dinosaurs: The two-metre-long and 1.50-metre-long animal ran on two powerful hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, bent teeth, short arms with shells and a long tail.
Had the species lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs to have these body features, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in the journal Science from Thursday.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangaea on the equator.
Tawa opens a new window to the early evolution of the dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us a lot about the relationship, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began digging on the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for deposits from the Triassic, team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History reports.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as a new species.
During the excavation, they brought together the remains of a total of five individuals.
Finding Confirms Theories About Dino Early History
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an extraordinary finding: "Dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts don’t necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current teachings, dinosaurs first emerged about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these Ur-Dinos is mostly controversial.
For example, experts argue about when the oaks split into their three main lines of development: the meat-eating theropods, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor, and also the birds, which are known as the "long-necked" steuris, the orchidsau, and the orchidsaurus.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
In the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of air sacs, as they also possessed the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air sacs, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
At Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were also apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air sacs, says Randall Irmis.
Since the associated line of the giant sauropods later also possessed air sacs and light-building bones, this useful innovation had probably already been brought about by the joint advance of both groups.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the lizards appeared there for the first time.
According to this, the three lines of development separated early and spread from South America over all parts of the earth, which formed a single land mass as Pangaea supercontinent at the time.
This is due to the fact that the team together with Tawa hallae found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods.
The three cannot be descended from a common, immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
There are, of course, contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, belonging to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
In his opinion, a distorted picture could result, because in South America there have simply been very few primitive Dino fossils preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to be found.
How the dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare sideline of the Reptilian tribe to the dominant agricultural animals of the Middle Ages is still a mystery.
During the Triassic, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today’s crocodiles and flight-saurians, and numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic, the dinosaurs spread around the world and developed many new species, while the kinship on the border from the Triassic to the Jurassic died out.
Success stories don’t last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass death that the dinosaurs accidentally survived, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so that they could beat the competition out of the field.
In any case, the success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite struck a group of animals that had also developed in the Triassic and since then has been tempting a shadow: the mammal.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and the signatories are international.
Professors at the University of Toronto stand on it, the University of Cambridge, the University of Vienna or from Berkeley in California.
