Support for brake manoeuvring in critical situations is now mandatory
As was the case with the ABS anti-lock braking system at the time, and as is currently the case with the stability control ESP, the auxiliary braking systems must become mandatory equipment in European cars in case of an emergency.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly approved passenger cars and light mini-carriers, for which the rest of the vehicles a Karenz deadline was set until the end of February 2011.
The European Union's decision to take the bait is aimed at improving the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many accidents due to their way of working.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the case of a critical brake maneuver, which detects the system on the brake pedal based on the brake strength performed by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident were no longer able to step on the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not fully braked.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The braking aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force into the braking system, thereby reducing the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car lags behind during the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assist.
There would be even fewer accidents – one expects that one in four accidents could be prevented by personal injury – as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (through radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while already exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver responds to this, the system helps him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already inevitable, the brake assistant exerts the maximum pressure on the brakes in order to keep the damage as low as possible.
