Acciona competes with Hochtief and Bouygues for its first motorway construction in Australia
Acciona is fighting for the approval of its first motorway in Australia, a market in which they are already represented as energy and water companies.
The construction is a tunnel that will cost 1.7 billion Australian dollars (about 1.047 billion euros).
The French company Bouygues and the German company Hochtief are its competitors.
A 5-kilometer-long tunnel in the Australian city of Brisbane, on the east coast, has become the best opportunity for Acciona to establish itself in the country as a construction company and highway operator.
The city administration wants the construction to be completed by the end of 2014.
After the Administration for Public-Private Cooperation (PPP) had decided to move the project forward according to a business plan set up by Ernst & Young, the Administration is already in possession of a final list of candidates for construction and toll management.
In anticipation of the offers presented in May, the estimated investments amount to 1.7 billion Australian dollars (1,047 billion euros), with three consortia, mainly made up of European construction companies, competing against each other in the last phase.
The group called Transcity is led by Acciona, the only Spanish company, and its partners are BMD and Ghella.
The first company is one of the largest construction companies in Australia, while the second, based in Italy, is one of the best specialists for underground construction.
Against the Acciona team, the Northern Direct consortium is formed by the British company Laing O'Rourke, the Australian Transfield, which is responsible for the infrastructure and the French Bouygues group.
The third and last consortium, which is in the narrower election, is called LBRJV, formed from the capital of the Australian Leighton (the subsidiary of the German construction company Hochtief, which in turn belongs to ACS), which also owns the local builder’s stone (in German owned by the German group of companies) and the company of the German company Ralfinger.
The Australian market for infrastructure promises enormous construction work and privatisation, but it has a hurdle to overcome, as you only get access through the purchase of a local construction company.
A strategy that the mentioned companies Hochtief or Bilfinger followed, in addition to Asian references, and which the Spanish construction giants have yet to pursue.
Even ACS has gained access to this market only through its 30% stake in Hochtief, owner of the aforementioned Leighton.
Millions of assets
Acciona is of the utmost importance to the industry in this geographical area, where it is already well known for its activities as an energy supplier and in the desalination industry.
Among other assets, it already has its largest wind farm (192 MW) in Victoria and leads the group of companies commissioned to build and manage the Adelaide desalination plant with a budget of 700 million.
Its intention is now to consolidate itself in these two areas and to use these synergies to gain access to the construction and infrastructure branches.
The underground toll route, which is funded by the Brisbane City Infrastructure Office and named Northern Link (Nordzubringer), has the purpose of passing the western highway in Toowong with the bypass road in Kelvin Grove (see map) on a length of 5 kilometers through the tunnel.
The timetable issued by the city administration foresees the allocation for summer 2010 and the start of construction work in December next year.
Although this toll route is expected to open for traffic in the last months of 2014, it is expected that construction work will continue until 2016.
The tunnel was designed in 2005.
It has two lanes in each direction, an electronic toll system and a complex ventilation system.
The Government of Queensland is contributing 500 million Australian dollars (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>308 million) to the funding.
